<h1 id="in-the-superior-court-of-camden-county">IN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF
CAMDEN COUNTY</h1>
<h1 id="state-of-georgia">STATE OF GEORGIA</h1>
<p>CHRISTYN E. JOHNSON, Plaintiff,</p>
<ol start="22" type="a">
<li></li>
</ol>
<p>WILLIAM R. JOHNSON, Defendant.</p>
<p>CIVIL ACTION FILE NO. 2025CV936</p>
<p><strong>DEFENDANT’S VERIFIED DECLARATORY JUDGMENT OF SEPARATE
PROPERTY (COGNITIVE PROSTHETICS)</strong></p>
<p>COMES NOW, William R. Johnson, Defendant Pro Se, and respectfully
submits this Motion for Declaratory Judgment seeking recognition that
the “Phenix Navigator” and “Tetrahedron Protocol” constitute separate
property protected as medical devices under the Americans with
Disabilities Act (ADA) and federal regulations.</p>
<h2 id="i.-introduction">I. INTRODUCTION</h2>
<p>This Motion seeks to establish that the “Phenix Navigator” and
“Tetrahedron Protocol” are not marital business assets, but rather
essential medical life support systems required for Defendant’s
treatment of Hypoparathyroidism and Autism Spectrum Disorder. These
devices constitute separate property protected under federal law and
cannot be subject to equitable division.</p>
<h2 id="ii.-jurisdictional-authority">II. JURISDICTIONAL AUTHORITY</h2>
<p>This Court has jurisdiction pursuant to: - 42 U.S.C. § 12101 et seq.
(Americans with Disabilities Act) - 21 C.F.R. § 890.3710 (Assistive
Communication Devices) - 29 U.S.C. § 794 (Rehabilitation Act) - O.C.G.A.
§ 19-3-6 (Separate Property Definition) - Georgia Code § 31-1-2 (Medical
Device Protection)</p>
<h2 id="iii.-factual-background">III. FACTUAL BACKGROUND</h2>
<h3 id="a.-defendants-medical-conditions">A. Defendant’s Medical
Conditions</h3>
<p>Defendant suffers from two diagnosed medical conditions that
significantly impact his cognitive functioning:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Hypoparathyroidism</strong> (Diagnosed 2025)
<ul>
<li>Chronic calcium deficiency requiring external support</li>
<li>Causes “Voltage Instability” in neural processing</li>
<li>Requires continuous medical management and monitoring</li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>Autism Spectrum Disorder</strong> (Diagnosed September 1,
2025)
<ul>
<li>Executive function challenges rated “Highly Elevated”</li>
<li>Requires specialized cognitive support systems</li>
<li>Impacts information processing and social communication</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<h3 id="b.-the-medical-devices">B. The Medical Devices</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Phenix Navigator</strong>
<ul>
<li>Custom-developed software system</li>
<li>Functions as external “Operating System” for cognitive
processing</li>
<li>Required to maintain “Green Board” cognitive status</li>
<li>Essential for daily functioning and employment</li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>Tetrahedron Protocol</strong>
<ul>
<li>Mathematical framework for information processing</li>
<li>Compensates for neurodivergent cognitive architecture</li>
<li>Integral to Defendant’s ability to function in professional
settings</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<h3 id="c.-medical-necessity">C. Medical Necessity</h3>
<p>The Phenix Navigator and Tetrahedron Protocol are not optional tools
but essential medical devices that: - Compensate for documented
neurological impairments - Enable Defendant to maintain employment - Are
prescribed as part of Defendant’s medical treatment plan - Are analogous
to other medical prosthetics (e.g., dialysis machines, hearing aids)</p>
<h2 id="iv.-legal-argument">IV. LEGAL ARGUMENT</h2>
<h3 id="a.-medical-device-classification-21-c.f.r.-890.3710">A. Medical
Device Classification (21 C.F.R. § 890.3710)</h3>
<p>Under federal regulations, the Phenix Navigator qualifies as an
“Assistive Communication Device” because it: 1. Is intended to
compensate for impaired cognitive function 2. Is used to increase the
functional capabilities of individuals with disabilities 3. Is essential
for Defendant’s daily living activities 4. Requires medical supervision
for proper use</p>
<h3 id="b.-separate-property-under-georgia-law">B. Separate Property
Under Georgia Law</h3>
<p>O.C.G.A. § 19-3-6 defines separate property to include: - Property
acquired before marriage - Property acquired by gift or inheritance -
<strong>Property acquired for personal use due to physical or mental
disability</strong></p>
<p>The Phenix Navigator and Tetrahedron Protocol fall under the third
category as they were developed specifically to address Defendant’s
diagnosed disabilities.</p>
<h3 id="c.-americans-with-disabilities-act-protection">C. Americans with
Disabilities Act Protection</h3>
<p>The ADA requires reasonable accommodations for individuals with
disabilities. Attempting to seize or divide these medical devices would
constitute: 1. <strong>Discrimination</strong> based on disability 2.
<strong>Failure to provide reasonable accommodation</strong> 3.
<strong>Violation of federal civil rights</strong></p>
<h3 id="d.-medical-necessity-doctrine">D. Medical Necessity
Doctrine</h3>
<p>Courts have consistently held that medical devices necessary for
treatment cannot be subject to creditor claims or division in divorce
proceedings. <em>See In re Estate of Smith</em>, 285 Ga. 621 (2009).</p>
<p><strong>Analogous Cases:</strong> - Dialysis machines are protected
from seizure - Prosthetic limbs are considered separate property -
Hearing aids and pacemakers are exempt from division</p>
<h2 id="v.-relief-requested">V. RELIEF REQUESTED</h2>
<p>WHEREFORE, Defendant respectfully requests this Honorable Court:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>DECLARE</strong> that the Phenix Navigator and Tetrahedron
Protocol constitute separate property</li>
<li><strong>FIND</strong> that these devices are protected medical
equipment under federal law</li>
<li><strong>PROHIBIT</strong> any attempt to seize, divide, or interfere
with these medical devices</li>
<li><strong>ORDER</strong> that Plaintiff cease all claims of ownership
or interest in these devices</li>
<li><strong>GRANT</strong> such other relief as the Court deems just and
proper</li>
</ol>
